# Mentara Engine — Architecture Deep Dive

## 1. End-to-End Flow: What Happens When a User Sends a Message

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant U as User (Browser)
    participant API as Express API
    participant Engine as TutorEngine
    participant CB as ContextBuilder
    participant LLM as LLM Provider
    participant TR as ToolRegistry
    participant SM as SessionManager
    participant DB as PostgreSQL

    U->>API: POST /api/class/:id/chat (SSE)
    API->>Engine: chatStream(classId, message)
    Engine->>CB: buildMessages(classId, message)
    
    Note over CB: 1. Get class state from DB
    CB->>SM: getClass(classId)
    SM->>DB: SELECT from classes
    DB-->>SM: class row
    SM-->>CB: ClassData (status, roadmap, module)
    
    Note over CB: 2. Build system prompt (phase-aware)
    CB->>CB: buildTutorSystemPrompt(classId, status)
    
    Note over CB: 3. Inject context addendum
    CB->>SM: getProgress(classId)
    SM->>DB: SELECT from progress
    DB-->>SM: progress row
    SM-->>CB: ProgressData
    CB->>CB: Append class state + progress to system prompt
    
    Note over CB: 4. Load & sanitize history
    CB->>SM: getHistory(classId)
    SM->>DB: SELECT from messages ORDER BY created_at
    DB-->>SM: message rows
    SM-->>CB: Message[]
    CB->>CB: sanitizeHistory() + compactContent()
    CB-->>Engine: Message[] (system + history + user)
    
    loop Agentic Loop (max 10 iterations)
        Engine->>LLM: chatStream(messages, tools)
        LLM-->>Engine: stream (text deltas + tool calls)
        Engine-->>U: SSE text_delta events
        
        alt No tool calls
            Engine->>SM: addMessage(assistant, content)
            Engine->>SM: getClass + getProgress
            Engine-->>U: SSE status + done
            Engine->>CB: summarizeIfNeeded() (background)
        else Has tool calls
            Engine->>SM: addMessage(assistant, content, tool_calls)
            loop Each tool call
                Engine->>TR: execute(toolName, args)
                TR-->>Engine: ToolResult
                Engine->>SM: addMessage(tool, result)
                alt UI Artifact tool
                    Engine-->>U: SSE tool_call event
                end
            end
            alt All UI artifacts
                Engine-->>U: SSE status + done (cascade prevention)
            else Has state tools
                Note over Engine: Continue loop → LLM sees tool results
            end
        end
    end
```

---

## 2. Phase State Machine

The class progresses through 5 phases. Each phase gives the LLM **different instructions**:

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> clarifying: User creates class
    clarifying --> negotiating: LLM calls update_class_state(roadmap)
    negotiating --> locked: LLM calls update_class_state(status=locked)
    locked --> in_progress: First teaching turn
    in_progress --> completed: All modules done
    completed --> [*]
    
    note right of clarifying: Ask 2-3 questions about depth, experience
    note right of negotiating: Present roadmap, accept modifications
    note right of locked: Teaching phase - introduce, explain, check, reinforce
    note right of completed: Present final mastery report
```

---

## 3. What Gets Injected Into Every LLM Call

Every time the user sends a message, the system builds this exact message array:

| # | Role | Content | Token Cost |
|---|------|---------|------------|
| 1 | `system` | Base prompt (~1200 tokens) + Phase instructions (~300-500 tokens) + Current class context (~200 tokens) + Progress summary (~100 tokens) | **~1800-2000** |
| 2 | `system` | Previous conversation summary (if history > 30 messages) | ~100-200 |
| 3-18 | Mixed | Last 16 messages (user, assistant, tool results) | **~2000-4000** |
| 19 | `user` | Current message | ~10-50 |

> [!WARNING]
> **Total prompt size: ~4,000-6,000+ tokens PER REQUEST.** The system prompt alone is ~2K tokens. With tool definitions for 11 tools adding another ~2K tokens, every request costs **~6,000-8,000 prompt tokens**. This is expensive for `gemini-3.1-flash-lite`.

---

## 4. Analysis: Are We Over-Constraining the LLM?

### Yes — In Several Critical Ways:

**Problem 1: Rigid Subtopic-by-Subtopic Enforcement**
The prompt says: *"Follow the roadmap module by module, subtopic by subtopic. Never skip ahead."* This removes the LLM's ability to:
- Adapt to student energy (skip boring basics if student already knows them)
- Make spontaneous connections between topics
- Respond to teachable moments

**Problem 2: Prescriptive Teaching Methodology**
Every subtopic must follow: Introduce → Explain → Check → Reinforce. This formulaic pattern:
- Makes every interaction feel robotic and predictable
- Prevents the LLM from using its natural conversational intelligence
- Forces questioning even when the student clearly understands

**Problem 3: Tool Call Mandates**
- *"ALWAYS call record_question_answer after evaluating ANY student answer"*
- *"After explaining 2-3 subtopics, use show_test"*
- *"At the end of each module, use show_test for a comprehensive assessment"*

This turns the LLM into a script executor rather than an adaptive tutor. The LLM spends tokens deciding **which mandatory tool to call** instead of **what's best for the student**.

**Problem 4: Context Overload**
We inject the full class state, progress summary, module details, and phase instructions on every turn. The LLM has `get_class_state` and `get_progress` tools to fetch this on demand, but we also pre-inject it — **wasteful duplication**.

### What We Do Right:

- **Phase-aware prompts** — Only showing relevant instructions prevents cross-phase confusion
- **Cascade prevention** — Stopping the loop after UI-only tool calls prevents wasted iterations
- **History sanitization** — Orphaned tool messages are correctly filtered
- **Background summarization** — Intelligent context compression

---

## 5. What We Borrowed From Claw Projects

| Pattern | picoclaw (Go) | tinyclaw (TS) | Mentara |
|---------|---------------|---------------|---------|
| **Tool Loop** | [RunToolLoop()](file:///D:/projects/picoclaw/pkg/tools/toolloop.go#34-158) — max iterations, tool registry, normalized tool calls | N/A (spawns CLI processes) | Direct copy of picoclaw's loop structure |
| **Session Manager** | JSON file storage, [GetOrCreate](file:///D:/projects/picoclaw/pkg/session/manager.go#42-61), [TruncateHistory](file:///D:/projects/picoclaw/pkg/session/manager.go#125-147), [SetSummary](file:///D:/projects/picoclaw/pkg/session/manager.go#114-124) | N/A (stateless CLI) | DB-backed version with same API shape |
| **History Sanitization** | [sanitizeHistory()](file:///c:/Users/Shivam%20singh/mentara/src/engine/context-builder.ts#107-143) from context builder comment: "picoclaw-inspired" | N/A | Directly adapted |
| **Tool Registry** | [ToolRegistry](file:///c:/Users/Shivam%20singh/mentara/src/tools/registry.ts#7-45) with [Register](file:///D:/projects/picoclaw/pkg/agent/loop.go#195-202), [Execute](file:///D:/projects/picoclaw/pkg/tools/base.go#10-11), `ToProviderDefs` | N/A | Same pattern, TS version |
| **Context Windowing** | Last N messages + optional summary | CLI `-c` flag for conversation continuation | Last 16 messages + LLM-generated summary |
| **Streaming** | Not supported | Not supported | **New** — full SSE streaming with delta forwarding |
| **UI Artifacts** | Not applicable (CLI/chat agents) | Not applicable | **New** — show_code, show_options, show_interactive, etc. |
| **Phase System** | Not applicable | Not applicable | **New** — state machine with phase-specific prompts |
| **Cascade Prevention** | Not present | Not present | **New** — UI artifact detection to prevent loop waste |

---

## 6. Do We Need a More Advanced Model?

### Current: `google/gemini-3.1-flash-lite-preview`

| Factor | Assessment |
|--------|-----------|
| **Tool calling reliability** | ⚠️ Flash-lite sometimes sends malformed JSON for `data` field (the "Unable to render" bug) |
| **Following complex system prompts** | ⚠️ Struggles with 2K+ token system prompts — may mix up phases or ignore instructions |
| **Teaching quality** | ❌ Explanations feel shallow; can't generate rich analogies or nuanced examples |
| **Context adherence** | ⚠️ With 6-8K prompt tokens, flash-lite often loses track of conversation context |
| **Creativity** | ❌ Highly formulaic responses; unable to craft truly engaging learning experiences |

### Recommendation:

| Model | Cost | Quality | Recommended For |
|-------|------|---------|----------------|
| `gemini-3.1-flash-lite` | $0.01/1M | ⭐⭐ | Summarization, simple Q&A only |
| `gemini-2.0-flash` | $0.10/1M | ⭐⭐⭐⭐ | **Best balance for Mentara** — good tool use, reasonable cost |
| `gemini-2.5-pro` | $1.25/1M | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ | Premium tier only — excellent teaching depth |
| `claude-3.5-sonnet` | $3.00/1M | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ | Best teaching quality, highest cost |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Flash-lite is fundamentally insufficient for an agentic teaching system.** It lacks the reasoning depth to manage phase transitions, generate rich visual artifacts, and maintain conversation coherence. At minimum, use `gemini-2.0-flash`.

---

## 7. Recommendations

### R1: Give the LLM Strategic Freedom
Replace the rigid Introduce→Explain→Check→Reinforce cycle with **outcome-based goals**:

```
Instead of:
  "For each subtopic: Introduce, Explain, Check, Reinforce"

Use:
  "Your goal for each subtopic is that the student achieves understanding.
   You decide the best approach — direct explanation, Socratic questioning,
   worked examples, or active practice. Adapt based on their responses."
```

### R2: Reduce Context Pre-Injection, Use On-Demand Tools
Stop injecting the full class context + progress into every system prompt. Instead:
- Inject only **phase** and **current subtopic name**
- Let the LLM call `get_class_state` / `get_progress` when it needs detailed state
- **Saves ~300-400 prompt tokens per request**

### R3: Replace Mandatory Tool Calls with Heuristic Nudges
Instead of *"ALWAYS call record_question_answer"*, use:
```
"If you asked a question and received an answer, consider recording it
 with record_question_answer for the student's revision tracking."
```

### R4: Add Reflection Prompts
After each module, instead of mandatory tests, let the LLM choose:
- A quiz for factual topics
- A mini-project for practical topics
- An open discussion for conceptual topics

### R5: Upgrade the Model
Switch from `gemini-3.1-flash-lite` to `gemini-2.0-flash` at minimum. The cost difference is negligible (~$0.10/1M vs $0.01/1M) but the quality improvement is dramatic.

### R6: Implement Adaptive Pacing
Add a simple heuristic: if the student answers 3 questions correctly in a row at the current difficulty, the LLM should increase difficulty or skip ahead. The system currently has no pacing intelligence.

### R7: Add RAG for Learning Content
Currently the LLM generates all educational content from its training data. For accuracy-critical topics, add a vector store of curated educational content that the LLM can retrieve from. This is especially important for technical topics where the LLM might hallucinate API details.

---

## 8. Comparison: How Others Do It

| Project | Approach |
|---------|----------|
| **Khan Academy (Khanmigo)** | Uses GPT-4 with Socratic method focus. Never gives answers directly — always asks guiding questions. Minimal system prompt, heavy reliance on model intelligence. |
| **Duolingo Max** | Highly structured: lesson scripts + LLM fills in adaptive practice. LLM has very little freedom — it generates within tight templates. |
| **Synthesis Tutor** | Multi-agent: one agent teaches, another evaluates, a third decides pacing. Each agent has a narrow, focused prompt. |
| **OpenAI Cookbook: Tutoring** | Recommends: minimal system prompt, strong model, RAG for knowledge base, separate evaluation pipeline. Warns against over-prompting. |
| **picoclaw** | General agent: no domain-specific instructions. Full tool freedom. Relies on model intelligence + conversation context. |
| **Mentara (current)** | Maximum instruction density: 2K system prompt, 11 tools, mandatory call patterns, rigid phase system. |

> [!TIP]
> The trend in 2025 is **less instruction, stronger model, better tools**. Khanmigo's success with GPT-4 shows that a strong model with a simple "be Socratic, never give answers" prompt outperforms a weak model with a 2K-token instruction manual.
